<TEXT>
dr priscilla white whose research 
sharply increased the survival rate of babies born to diabetic 
women died at age 89 after a long illness 
white died saturday at her home in this boston suburb according 
to a statement from the joslin diabetes center in boston 
her studies identified ways to decrease the risk of maternal and 
child death in pregnancies complicated by diabetes the statement 
said 
whites research and the treatment process she developed 
increased the fetal survival rate around the country from 54 
percent in the 1920s to about 97 percent in the late 1970s and 
1980s it said 
born in boston white attended radcliffe college and graduated 
third in her class from tufts university medical school in 1923 
she joined a diabetes practice headed by elliott p joslin and 
in 1924 became the youngest member of the team that established the 
clinic now known as the joslin diabetes center 
white taught at harvard medical school and was an assistant 
professor of medicine at tufts she received numerous honors and 
was the first woman to receive the banting medal the american 
diabetes associations highest scientific award 
in her research white found that a fetus of a diabetic mother 
often would be healthy a month before delivery but would die if 
allowed to go full term she concluded that babies of diabetic 
women should be delivered by caesarean section at eight months 
she gradually discovered that babies could remain in the womb an 
extra week to develop she also learned that although infants of 
diabetic mothers usually are normal or larger than normal in size 
despite premature birth they require the same special care needed 
for premature infants 
</TEXT>
