a key plutonium production plant at the 
hanford nuclear reservation reopened sunday to process spent 
nuclear fuel that has been stuck in the plant since it was shut 
down a year ago the government said 
energy secretary james d watkins authorized the reopening 
friday based on a review by the department and the need to improve 
safety at the facility said department of energy spokesman tom 
bauman 
the plutoniumuranium extraction plant takes nuclear fuel rods 
from hanfords n reactor and dissolves them to extract plutonium 
and uranium the plutonium must be processed further at another 
facility for use in nuclear weapons 
the n reactor has been closed since late 1986 but purex 
continued to operate until last december to reduce a large 
stockpile of irradiated fuel 
westinghouse hanford co which operates the nuclear production 
complex for the government said it shut the plant down because 
operators did not follow procedures in handling a loss of steam 
pressure 
doe officials have said previously that the shutdown of the 
purex plant would not hurt the countrys ability to make nuclear 
weapons 
a review of safety requirements and procedures along with 
retraining of about 500 purex workers was completed in march 
equipment repairs and improvements to waste treatment systems at 
the 33yearold plant delayed the resumption of operations bauman 
said 
purex is expected to remain open for four to six weeks to finish 
processing material that was in the plant when it was shut down 
bauman said 
then the plant will be shut for another year to make additional 
modifications and improvements before resuming the processing of 
spent fuel in storage at hanford bauman said processing that 
inventory is expected to take until 1995 
from purex plutonium is sent to hanfords plutonium finishing 
plant which has been operating only periodically for the past 
year bauman said that plant will gear up eventually to handle the 
