<TEXT>
britains 15 percent interest rates are 
discouraging shoppers from splurging on christmas gifts and 
threatening the countrys retailers with the worst selling season 
in nine years 
many stores are packed with people but many seem to be 
modernday scrooges and arent buying much christmas sales are 
patchy 
a lastminute flurry of purchases is expected but this wont 
salvage the crucial season experts say 
the vote on this christmas will be that it was a very poor 
christmas said nick bubb a retail analyst with the investment 
firm morgan stanley international in london its going to be 
flat 
the disappointing prechristmas season has prompted many stores 
to start slashing prices before britains traditional january 
sales many also likely will defy the law requiring them to close 
on sundays and risk a fine of 1600 to stay open on the day before 
christmas 
the poor sales trend reflects a monthslong downturn and its 
bad news for retailers profits and their stock prices which 
generally have been depressed on londons stock exchange 
but its good news for consumers who are benefiting from sales 
in jewelry consumer electronics clothing and home furnishings 
its also positive for prime minister margaret thatchers 
conservative government because slower sales are a sign that its 
antiinflation policy is working 
its been a bad year christmas will make or break some 
people said harry shepherd director of the oxford street 
association oxford street is londons main shopping street 
shepherd said he expects retailers to eke out an overall 1 
percent to 2 percent sales gain but that wont be enough to cover 
higher costs 
