that the very rich will always be rich and the retailers selling 
three pairs of knickers for 99 pence are still doing very well 
its the mass in the middle who are suffering he said 
consumer electronics and furniture retailers will be hurt the 
most bubb predicted 
experts agree that trading conditions are tough because of the 
higher interest rates which the government has pushed to an 
eightyear peak to fight resurgent inflation inflation is running 
at an annual rate of 77 percent 
the higher interest rates have squeezed british homeowners who 
mostly hold adjustable rate mortgages and have seen their monthly 
payments climb sharply 
before the economy began overheating more than 18 months ago 
britain enjoyed a fiveyear steady economic expansion fueled by 
consumer demand 
but growth in consumer spending has slowed from 7 percent in 
1988 to an expected 4 percent in 1989 and is predicted to slow to 
1 percent in 1990 
the slowdown has been showing up in the governments retail 
sales figures 
in november sales declined a sharp 08 percent from october 
the government announced recently that meant sales for the latest 
three months rose 11 percent over a year ago the lowest such 
growth rate since june 1982 figures from the central statistical 
office show 
the retailers themselves are having to pay the higher interest 
rates and rents are pricey too wage costs also are up because 
fewer teenage workers are available 
although the inflation rate is high retailers cant raise 
prices to enhance their profits bubb said 
their promotions arent going to help the bottom line 
ratners jewelry stores for example are offering the equivalent 
of 80 gift vouchers for every 240 worth of sales while the tandy 
